      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "The instructions are pretty clear. It only auto imports the <code>unambiguous</code> classes. And I have been using it since past two days on my 3000+ classes project. Works like a charm. Thanks for sharing."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 173186,
        "reputation" : 4709,
        "user_id" : 401712,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8ab83e913223d2bee3eb4c4b5629122a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Dario Seidl",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/401712/dario-seidl"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1689325662,
      "post_id" : 50092612,
      "comment_id" : 135200523,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "When you have ambiguous imports, and you know that you never want to import some of the options, you can exclude hem in &quot;Preferences &gt; Editor &gt; General &gt; Auto Import &gt; Exclude from auto-import and completion&quot;. That way, &quot;Add unambiguous imports on the fly&quot; works more often."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5306113,
      "reputation" : 4187,
      "user_id" : 4233951,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 56,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/668f3fdfcdb37c7c029f009f016341fc?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "atlas_scoffed",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4233951/atlas-scoffed"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 35,
    "last_activity_date" : 1543274390,
    "last_edit_date" : 1543274390,
    "creation_date" : 1525048132,
    "answer_id" : 50092612,
    "question_id" : 31211842,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I think the best solution, though not exactly the same as Eclipse/Netbeans, is to change the 'Optimize Imports' settings.</p>\n\n<p>Under <code>Preferences &gt; Editor &gt; General &gt; Auto Import</code></p>\n\n<p>Set <code>Add unambiguous imports on the fly</code></p>\n\n<p>Edit: Using this method, when there <em>are</em> ambiguous imports, IntelliJ will let you know, and you can then use <kbd>Alt</kbd> + <kbd>Enter</kbd> method outlined in the <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/37152567/4233951\">answer by Wuaner</a></p>\n\n<p>I find that, almost always, the most appropriate Import is at the top of the list. </p>\n"
  }, {
